The reason the _Student_ class is not retaining the information you&#39;re provided is due to the code within the _constructor method_.

You are assigning the fields incorrectly.  
The _[this](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/javaOO/thiskey.html)_ keyword refers to the class instance context, and not the scope context.

```java
Name = this.Name;
BirthYear = this.BirthYear;
BirthMonth =this.BirthMonth;
BirthDay=this.BirthDay;
GPA=this.GPA;
```

Flip these assignments.

```java
this.Name = Name;
this.BirthYear = BirthYear;
this.BirthMonth = BirthMonth;
this.BirthDay = BirthDay;
this.GPA = GPA;
```

Output

```none
Name:David King
Age:18
GPA: 3.211
Name:Jane Hall
Age:21
GPA: 3.9662
Name:Mary Reed
Age:19
GPA: 2.8
Name:John Diaz
Age:20
GPA: 2.916
```

Here are some recommendations for your code.

You can obtain a year value by simply subtracting the _Calendar_ values.

```java
Calendar c = Calendar.getInstance();
int y = c.get(Calendar.YEAR);
return y &lt; 0 ? 0 : y - BirthYear;
```

Or, use a _[Period](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/20/docs/api/java.base/java/time/Period.html)_ object.

```java
LocalDate bd = LocalDate.of(BirthYear, BirthMonth, BirthDay);
Period p = Period.between(LocalDate.now(), bd);
return Math.max(p.getYears(), 0);
```

Store your _fractional_ values&amp;mdash;i.e., GPA&amp;mdash;as _String_ or _[BigDecimal](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/20/docs/api/java.base/java/math/BigDecimal.html)_ objects.

Additionally, I would use a _[String#split](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/20/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/String.html#split(java.lang.String))_ on each line over a _Scanner#next_ call.

```java
